text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Asian discrimination in South Park%0a%0a:Author: NickG%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aSouth Park often discriminates against a number of groups, and their representation of Asian is very stereotypical and offensive.%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe following clip is one of many examples of the show South Park portraying Asians in a stereotypical way, in part by exaggerating stereotypes associated with how Asians pronounce English words.%0a[[https://youtu.be/xWf8JcRsq9k]]%0a%0aIn the clip, it features two Chinese-Americans giving a talk, but it is overexaggerating a common accent among Asian-American immigrants in a discriminatory way. Specifically, it is making fun of the pronunciation of [l] in English words as [r] and portraying it as ungrammatical. In the clip, the characters are depicted pronouncing "rely" as [ɹɪˈraɪ] instead of the SAE pronunciation [ɹɪˈlaɪ], "intellect" as [ˈɪntərekt] instead of [ˈɪntəlekt], and "look" as [rʊk] instead of [lʊk]. The exaggeration of this linguistic pattern alongside other stereotypical portrayals of the characters gives the impression that this accent is somehow inferior to SAE or ungrammatical in some way.%0a%0aThis accent is common among many Asian immigrants in America, in part because many Asian languages, especially East Asian, do not have a phonological distinction between the [l] and [r] sound. In this clip specifically, South Park is making fun of a Chinese-American accent, but they have portrayed many Asians in a similar way. In every instance, the overemphasis on the linguistic differences between native English speakers and Asian speakers serves to present them as worse Engish speakers than natives, which is an inherently discriminatory portrayal.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210502-184759-609680#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Lampooning vs. Reinforcing stereotypes %0a-> - kevinx%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a(warning: language)%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=enOQozXwctc%0a%0aIn the above clip, both Asian characters are voiced by series co-creator Trey Parker. The punchline of these characters is their accents, which cause them to pronounce "city" [cɪti] as "shitty" [ʃɪti]. %0a%0aSouth Park has always been a show that relies on outrage comedy. In most cases, it justifies this by rightfully lampooning antiquated stereotypes such as the "Token Black" character in a show or the depiction Canadians in America. In these examples, South Park subverts expectations to criticize a stereotype -- by explicitly naming a character Token Black to make acknowledge and make fun of the show's early lack of diversity or by animating Canadian characters as anatomically different to Americans to make fun of how Americans see themselves as superior to Canadians.%0a%0aHowever, in the case of depiction of Asian stereotypes, sometimes the show doesn't as much lampoon them as harmfully reinforce them. In the clip in the main article, it could be argued that the show is flipping the script on how white comedians like to mock Asian accents by having Asian comedians mock white people. However, in both clips, the show doesn't make an effort to criticize the fact that Asians are so often mocked for their accent, but instead joins in using the accent as part of the punchline.%0a%0aIn a later episode of South Park, it is revealed that the owner of City Wok is, in fact, a white character who believes himself to be Asian. This backhandedly justifies the use of a stereotypical Asian accent, but it's hard to say if this is the show retconning the character to avoid backlash or genuinely changing its stance.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210502-184759-609680#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: C:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
